On Escalation Ticket # 00419505 the new comment has been added: Robert Zavalczki:

Please check that the Endpoint protector server at 10.26.222.101 is reachable from
the proxy server at 172.30.0.22. Are the Endpoint Protector server and the proxy server in the same network?


To test the reachability open a terminal and run this command:


--- CODE ---
curl -vvvvvv https://10.26.222.101/index.php --proxy 172.30.0.22:8080
--- CODE ---

and send us the output from the terminal. @WaitingOnEngineer

On Escalation Ticket # 00419505 the new comment has been added: @Robert, the customer attached a new log file to the ticket, please take a look if the issue is related to their proxy or not. As discussed, the communication between the EPP client and server rely on a client certificate (mTLS) and we should see if their proxy strips that certificate making it impossible for the EPP server to authenticate the EPP.
During my call with him last week, he whitelisted the server IP inside of Ethernet > Proxies but it still did not work.

Thank you

On Escalation Ticket # 00419505 the new comment has been added: Robert Zavalczki:

Based on the logs, unless the EPP server is not running, this is the customer's networking problem and not our issue.

A private IP address can't be accessed from the internet. If their proxy server is on the internet (or in a different network) it won't be able to reach the EPP server in a different private network.

They should sort out their networking issues by themselves. Also the latest logs are redacted and the involved IP addresses are not visible.

FYI @WaitingOnEngineer

On Escalation Ticket # 00419505 the new comment has been added: Thank for your time today @Alex!
As we saw during our session, when the client is installed, and the proxy is enabled, the client will take the configuration of the proxy and it will not communicate with the server.
When the proxy is disabled, the newly installed client will communicate with the server.
We found 2 workarounds for this issue:
1. to install the client without the proxy enabled. and after it is installed, to enable it.
2. to remove from /etc/epp/options.ini the line for the proxy and also the "cert.xxxxx..." file from the same folder. The client could communicate with the server after that.

As discussed with the customer, please let us know if we can provide a solution/script to the customer for the present issue.
Thank you again!
